context: May wynne of me moo fees thus
To have moo floures swiche seven
He stood unnethes seyde he wordes mo
Ther fil as it bifalleth tymes mo
O noble wyves ful of heigh prudence
Of quyksilver withouten wordes mo
Now good sires what wol ye bet than wel
Forestes parkes ful of wilde deer
Whan thritty tirauntz ful of cursednesse
For which thise woful maydens ful of drede
What sholde I mo ensamples heerof sayn
Certeyn he knew of briberyes mo
Tel me anon withouten wordes mo
As ye han herd what nedeth wordes mo
In which ther were moo ymages
And with perre moo pynacles
And moo loves newe begonne
And moo loves casuelly
Mo discordes moo jelousies
Mo discordes moo jelousies
Mo murmures and moo novelries
Mo murmures and moo novelries
And moo dissymulacions
And moo berdys in two houres
And also moo renovelaunces
Mo lovedayes and acordes
And eke of loves moo eschaunges
As corbetz ful of ymageries
Of songes ful of armonye
Good werkes shal yow noght availle
Han these sory creatures
Where thou maist most tidynges here
Terme of his lyf what nedeth wordes mo
And seyde Sire what nedeth wordes mo
What ladyes fairest been or best daunsynge
With othere rytes mo and atte laste
I feele my lymes stark and suffisaunt
Of scoletermes Wyser men than thow
Upon a bench of turves fressh and grene
Upon hir lendes ful of many a goore
And right anon withouten wordes mo
Withouten wordes mo they goon to bedde
He sit hym up withouten wordes mo
Sixty cubites long and sevene in brede
This kyng of kynges proud was and elaat
His nayles whitter than the lylye flour
And wente his wey withouten wordes mo
There been mo sterres God wot than a payre
With aungels ful of cleernesse and of light
And deyntees mo than been in my knowyng
That fresshe floures blew and white and rede
As make it with thise argumentes tough
So were his dayes sory outher gladde
To telle in short withouten wordes mo
Tho besy wrecches ful of wo and drede
A thousand sikes hotter than the gleede
Medled with pleyntes new his wo to feede
Withouten wordes mo I wol be ded
And with his teeris salt hire brest byreyned
Among the Grekis ful of worthynesse
The gydyng of thi bemes bright an houre
Biheld the toures heigh and ek the halles
For which withouten any wordes mo
Was in his nedes prest and corageous
Who shal now trowe on any othes mo
Of Brugges were his hosen broun
I trowe he hadde wyves mo than oon
And ech of hem hadde wyves mo than two
For I shal telle ensamples mo than ten
He knew of hem mo legendes and lyves
Of Venus werkes worth his olde sho
And therwithal he knew of mo proverbes
But now kan no man se none elves mo
